, "prob": 0.5867618322372437, "span": {"begin": 687, "end": 691}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "citrus", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.6559267640113831, "span": {"begin": 700, "end": 706}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:9260"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "pectin", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.5318385362625122, "span": {"begin": 707, "end": 713}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "HCT116 cells", "obj": "cell_line", "prob": 0.9486494064331055, "span": {"begin": 738, "end": 750}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "HCT-116 cells", "obj": "cell_line", "prob": 0.9676094651222229, "span": {"begin": 825, "end": 838}}], "text": "Numerous instances of chemicals both inhibiting SDH/complex II and generating excess mitochondrial superoxide have been reported.  2-thenoyltrifluoroacetone (TTFA) and the anticancer agent lonidamine have been shown to inhibit succinate dehydrogenation to fumarate in a variety of cell lines (DB-1, HepG2, HCT116 and HeLa), and to inhibit the generation of fumarate and malate (into which fumarate is converted by the TCA cycle enzyme fumarase) in isolated mouse liver mitochondria.&nbsp; Both compounds additionally lead to an increase in reactive oxygen (ROS) species generation in DM-1 cells (Guo et al, 2016). Similarly, trans-4,5-dihydroxy-2-cyclopentene-1-one (DCHP), derived from heat-treated citrus pectin inhibits complex II, in HCT116 cells, and leads to an increase in ROS generation in mitochondria isolated from HCT-116 cells (Chen et al, 2021).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:48:28 +0000 2026"}